parser

Class Parser

  • java.lang.Object
    • parser.Parser

  • public class Parser
extends java.lang.Object
    This is the main parser class. It has some instance variables, but this whole program is really designed to process one Judo file in its lifetime, there's too must static state that breaks subsequent runs.

    • Constructor Detail

      • Parser

        public Parser(java.lang.String filename)
        Ingests the Judo file at the given filename. The file is broken down line-by-line, which means no single valid statement spans more than one line, including array literals. No actual Java code is produced until one of the Parse methods is called.
        Parameters:
        filename - The path to the Judo file to translate to java.

      • Parser

        public Parser(java.lang.String whitespace,
              java.lang.String... lines)
        Testing constructor
        Parameters:
        whitespace - characters to use as the "file"'s whitespace
        lines - Lines representing the "file".

        Returns:

      • countIndents

        public int countIndents(java.lang.CharSequence line,
                        int ln)
        Counts the number of indents at the beginning of line. Uses the class's whitespace instance variable which is determined in the constructor based on the Judo file. Will throw an IndentationError if the whitespace is found to contain a mix of tabs and spaces or a whitespace character that differs from that in the whitespace instance variable. Also throws an IndentationError if the number of whitespace characters isn't in line with the expected amount, i.e. a line indented with 6 spaces in a file that uses 4 spaces.
        Parameters:
        line - The line whose leading whitespace to use.
        ln - The line's line number.
        Returns:
        The number of indents counted.

      • parseFull

        public java.lang.String parseFull(java.lang.String className)
        Using the already ingested Judo file (from the constructor), attempts to create an entire legal Java file and return it as a string for the consumer to do with as they please.
        Parameters:
        className - The classname to give the new Java file.
        Returns:
        An entire legal Java file, translated from the Judo file whose path was provided in the constructor.

      • armMatcher

        public java.util.regex.Matcher armMatcher(java.util.regex.Pattern toUse,
                                          java.lang.CharSequence toMatch)
        This has to be done to set internal state of the matcher to be ready to do things like query the groups. Thanks OOP. This method makes no guarantees that the returned matcher actually matches toMatch.
        Parameters:
        toUse - The pattern from which to generate the matcher.
        toMatch - The string to match against.
        Returns:
        A matcher which is "armed", that is, ready to have its groups queried.

      • initMatcherType

        private Type initMatcherType(java.util.regex.Matcher initMatcher)
        Given a matching matcher from pattern RAY_INIT, returns the type of the ray being initialized. RAY_INIT allows users to create a type ray of an arbitrary size with the syntax 
        let arr = i{100}
        Which would initialize an int array of size 100.
        Parameters:
        initMatcher - An armed and matching matcher of the RAY_INIT pattern.
        Returns:
        The appropriate type for this ray.

      • validateByScalarType

        private void validateByScalarType(java.lang.CharSequence expression,
                                  Type expected)
        Validates the given expression under the grammar pertaining to expected. Will throw IllegalArgumentException if expected is a ray type. Uses the throwing version of validation.
        Parameters:
        expression - A scalar type, i.e. INT, BOOL, or STRING
        expected - The type expression is expected to validate as.

      • typeToGrammar

        private Grammar typeToGrammar(Type t)
        Returns the Grammar pertaining to the given type
        Parameters:
        t - The type of the grammar to fetch
        Returns:
        Math, Bool, or String grammar for scalar t's, or a RayGrammar for anything else.

      • finalReplacements

        private java.lang.String finalReplacements(java.lang.CharSequence expression,
                                           Type t)
        Intelligently replaces all necessary replacements for Java legality. Should be done just before being appended to the Java StringBuilder, because the result of these replacements will no longer be valid Judo.
        Parameters:
        expression - The expression to replace in.
        t - The type of expression.
        Returns:
        expression with the necessary replacements made, which may actually be none at all. For example strings don't need any replacements done.

      • parseBlock

        public int parseBlock(int lineStart,
                      ScopeStack scopes,
                      java.lang.StringBuilder java,
                      java.lang.String currWhitespace)
        Parses an entire block of Judo starting at the index lineStart.
        Parameters:
        lineStart - The first line of the block to parse in the instance variable lines.
        scopes - The ScopeStack to query and modify as the block is parsed and translated.
        java - The ongoing Java document which is appended to by the various handle* functions, all of which are called from in here.
        currWhitespace - The current amount of whitespace to put before each line of Java. This doesn't work perfectly, but it's a little better than zero indentation.
        Returns:
        The total number of lines that were parsed as a result of this call, including all recursive calls.

      • handleAssignment

        public void handleAssignment(Parser.Line line,
                             java.lang.StringBuilder java,
                             ScopeStack scopes)
        Handles the assignment, and thus creation, of a new variable. This statement always begins with a "let", and the type of the value is inferred based on various things. If it is a variable, it takes on the type of that variable. If it is an expression, Grammars are tried on it until one validates. The type connected to the variable here cannot be changed.
        Parameters:
        line - The line to process.
        java - The ongoing Java file to append translated java to.
        scopes - The ScopeStack representing current variables.

      • handleReassignment

        public void handleReassignment(Parser.Line line,
                               java.lang.StringBuilder java,
                               ScopeStack scopes)
        Handles the reassignment of variables. This is different from assignment in that it does not begin with the keyword let. If the variable being reassigned didn't already exist, a VariableError will be thrown. Also, the value being assigned to the variable must be of the same type as the variable was originally.
        Parameters:
        line - The line to process.
        java - The ongoing Java file to append translated java to.
        scopes - The ScopeStack representing current variables.

      • handleIf

        public void handleIf(Parser.Line line,
                     java.lang.StringBuilder java,
                     ScopeStack scopes)
        handles our if statement, which is 
        if condition:
     do stuff
        As with all conditionals, the condition does not have to be in parentheses.
        Parameters:

        java - The ongoing Java file to append translated java to.
        scopes - The ScopeStack representing current variables.

      • handleElf

        public void handleElf(Parser.Line line,
                      java.lang.StringBuilder java,
                      ScopeStack scopes)
        Handles our elf statement, which is 
        efl condition:
     do stuff
        We went with one word because our language is whitespace sensitive, and also because we thought elf is funny. There must be an if statement already "open" for an elf statement to be valid.
        Parameters:
        line - The line to process.
        java - The ongoing Java file to append translated java to.
        scopes - The ScopeStack representing current variables.
